So...the lesson learned here is that while the progress made is encouraging, we need to follow the old adage, "trust, but verify." 

I want a denuclearization agreement, but one that NK won't back out of...again.

2013-2015: NK once again tests a nuclear weapon and does so two more times in the following two years. Sanctions widely supported by the international community are levied by the U.S. and China against North Korea for their provocative actions.

2011-2012: Kim Jong Il dies and is replaced my Kim Jong Un. The US and NK soon agree to an end in nuclear enrichment and weapons testing in exchange for food and aid. This deal collapses after North Korea launches a satellite, violating the agreement.

2007: A new agreement is reached with NK. They agree to disarm & let inspectors into the country
 
2008: NK doesn't meet requirements agreed upon in the previous treaty, and reopens closed reactors.
 
2009: NK launches a rocket, removes inspectors, tests another nuclear weapon...
2006: North Korea rejects denuclearization, testing their first nuclear warhead. In response, the UN implements economic sanctions.

2005: After two years of negotiations and frustrating set-backs, North Korea finally agrees to a statement of principles that banned their nuclear weapons. But problems arose again when NK could not accept U.S. inspection protocols…

2001-2002: President Bush reviews NK policies & deems them ineffective. Evidence is found that NK continued building nuclear weapons after signing a prohibitive treaty. When confronted about this, NK expelled nuclear inspectors and withdrew from disarmament treaties…

1993-94: North Korea tried to bar nuclear inspectors from inspecting waste sites. In response Pres. Clinton threatened sanctions. With tensions high, President Jimmy Carter went to negotiate a new deal regarding nuclear inspections, he was successful and the crisis was averted…

1991: President George H.W. Bush announces he will withdraw nuclear weapons from the Korean Peninsula, and North and South Korea sign a treaty prohibiting nuclear weapons and their testing in the future…

THREAD: As the high stakes North Korea meeting approaches, all of us need perspective and history. Don’t get me wrong, I have high hopes, but those who don’t remember history are doomed to repeat it. Share this thread to help everyone learn from the past…
